es on Contributors -- tIndex of Names0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOctavio Paz is one of the most recognized Latin American writers. His essays offer a sophisticated critique of global modernity. Although his work has advanced many of the arguments that orient our contemporary debates in the social sciences and in philosophy, it has hardly ever been seriously taken into consideration in these disciplines. The volume suggests that this may have been a mistake. Its authors indicate ways in which Paz' essays can be read as substantial contributions to the contemporary debates in various fields. The aim of this book is to present to a non-Spanish speaking audience some of the discussions about Paz' offerings to the ongoing debates. It also wants to make a clear statement: a critique of our contemporary modernity must go hand in hand with a non-exclusive intercultural understanding of Humanism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 4aCritique of Modernity. 4aCultural Theory. 4aHuman. 4aHumanism. 4aInterculturalism. 4aLatin America. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aLiterature. 4aRomance Studies. 4aSocial Philosophy. 4aSocial Theory. 4aSpanish Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Spanish & Portuguese.2bisacsh  aCritique of Modernity.  aCultural Theory.  aHuman.  aHumanism.  aInterculturalism.  aLatin America.  aLiterary Studies.  aLiterature.  aRomance Studies.  aSocial Philosophy.  aSocial Theory.  aSpanish Literature.1 aCapetillo-Ponce, Jorge, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEcheverría, Bolívar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFidalgo, Juan Álvarez-Cienfuegos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGallo, R